{{Infobox comedian <!-- for individuals - see Template:Infobox comedian for usage --> | name = Tanyalee Davis | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | pseudonym = | birth_name = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_date = 27 November 1970 | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = | medium = | nationality = | education = | alma_mater = | active = | employer = | genre = | subject = | spouse = | domesticpartner = | children = | parents = | relatives = | notable_work = | memorials = | signature = | website = {{URL|tanyaleedavis.com/}} | footnotes = | module = }} '''Tanyalee Davis''' (born 27 November 1970) is a [[Canadian]] [[comedian]] who tours extensively throughout the world but mostly in the UK. Davis also obtained her [[US citizenship]] in the fall of 2010.
Davis has a form of [[dwarfism]] called [[diastrophic dysplasia]] and has a height of {{convert|3|ft|6|in|cm}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hlntv.com/video/2012/10/04/dwarfs-build-successful-careers-comedians|title=Dwarfs build successful careers as comedians|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>
==Career== In November 1999, she placed second in the [[Seattle]] Comedy Competition. She was the first woman in 10 years to make it into the finals. In October 2012, she placed sixth overall in the San Francisco Comedy festival. In April 2001, she headlined at the [[Melbourne International Comedy Festival]].
She won the 2003 Norman G. Brooks Standup Comedy Scholarship Competition held at the [[Hollywood]] [[The Improv|Improv]]. In August 2003, she was part of the "US Comedy Invasion" show, performing at the world’s largest arts festival, the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] in [[Scotland]]. She then embarked on a UK tour in the spring of 2004. She featured at the Edinburgh Fringe again in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theedinburghreporter.co.uk/2013/08/edinburgh-festival-fringe-2013-review-interview-tanyalee-davis-big-trouble-in-little-gina/|title=Edinburgh Festival Fringe 2013 – REVIEW & INTERVIEW – Tanyalee Davis – Big Trouble in Little ‘Gina ****|date=2013-08-17|language=en-US|access-date=2016-06-29}}</ref>
In the US, she was featured on [[Last Comic Standing]] in 2004, on [[Animal Planet]]'s hit show, ''[[Pit Boss]]'' (2012) as well as ''[[Dr Drew]]'' on [[CNN]]. Previous credits include ''[[Austin Powers in Goldmember]]'' movie teaser, "For the Love of Money"(Movie 2002), [[MTV]]’s Bash of Carson Daly (TV 2003) and the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] network's [[reality show]] ''[[30 Seconds to Fame]]''.
In 2005, she performed as part of the ''Abnormally Funny People'' show, with Steve Best, [[Liz Carr]], [[Steve Day]], [[Chris McCausland]] and Simon Minty. As part of the Edinburgh Festival Fringe the following year she appeared with Carr in ''Bravetarts''. In 2007 she performed her one-woman show ''Little Do They Know''. She then revamped the fringe show and had a six-month contract at the [[Clarion Hotel and Casino]] in [[Las Vegas]] in 2011.
In August 2013, Davis went back to the Edinburgh Fringe with her new one-person show "Big Trouble In Little 'Gina" which was based on a terrible medical ordeal starting at the end of 2012.
In 2011-2012 Davis was a series regular on the UK's [[Channel 4]] TV show ''[[I'm Spazticus]]''.
Davis was featured in a few British-produced programmes such as [[Sky (United Kingdom)|Sky TV]]'s documentary of the making of ''Abnormally Funny People'' as well as ITV's ''SuperHuman: World's Smallest People'' (which also aired on [[TLC (TV network)|TLC]] in the US). Her extensive spinal surgery was a focus in this show.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2008/jul/08/comedian-davis-wont-let-anything-keep-her-down/|title=Comedian Davis won’t let anything keep her down|date=2008-07-08|access-date=2016-06-29}}</ref> On 28 August 2013, she appeared as a special guest on the live comedy Paralympics show ''[[The Last Leg]]'', discussing [[Jim Davidson]]'s comments about "midgets".
In 2015 she appeared on two major UK television shows, both on [[BBC]]. The first was ''[[The John Bishop Show]]'' - a variety show hosted by the top notch Liverpudlian, John Bishop. The second show was ''[[Live at the Apollo (TV series)|Live at the Apollo]]'' - with their first ever Christmas edition. Both sets were very well received according to social media.{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}}
On 15 July 2018, Davis was "harassed and humiliated" after a train guard for [[Great Western Railway]] attempted to force her to move her mobility scooter from a disabled space on the train. The guard made an announcement to the train passengers that she was "causing problems" and threatened to call the [[British Transport Police|police]] if she did not move and give her space to a woman with a pram. An investigation into the incident was begun by the rail company.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-norfolk-44858107|title=Disabled comedian 'humiliated' on train|date=17 July 2018|publisher=|accessdate=18 July 2018|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-norfolk-44858107|title=Disabled comedian 'humiliated' on train|date=2018-07-17|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-07-17|language=en-GB}}</ref> On the 20 July 2018, Davis was left stranded on a train when staff at [[York railway station]] failed to arrive with a ramp, and the train departed for [[Darlington]], adding an hours delay to her journey.<ref>{{cite news| title =Tanyalee Davis: More train trouble for disabled comedian | work = | publisher =BBC | date =21 July 2018 | url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-norfolk-44910639 }}</ref>
